Welcome to the UI gym, where every element is either a heavyweight champ or a featherweight contender. (Spoiler: most are just bench-pressing pixels.)

## Wait, Why Is My Button Yelling At Me?

Ever seen a screen where everything is screaming for attention? It's like a toddler birthday party: everyone's loud, nobody's special, and you just want to go home. That's what happens when you don't control _weight_.

But what is "weight"? It's not just size. It's:

1. **Size** (Big = "LOOK AT ME!")
2. **Color value** (Darker or more saturated = heavier. Neon pink? That's a visual kettlebell.)
3. **Font weight** (Bold is heavy. Thin is "I skipped leg day.")
4. **Fill vs. stroke** (Solid shapes = sumo wrestler. Outlined = yoga instructor.)

Mix these up and you can make a tiny thing feel huge, or a big thing feel like a whisper. Magic!

## The "Everything Is Important" Disaster

Let's meet a card where every element is the same weight. It's the design equivalent of a monotone lecture.

<Preview>
  <div class="p-5 bg-white font-sans max-w-sm border rounded-lg space-y-1">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Product Name</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">$49.00</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">4.5 stars</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">128 reviews</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">In stock</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-2">All elements the same. User doesn't know where to look.</p>
  </div>
</Preview>

## Give Everything a Role

<Preview>
  <div class="p-5 bg-white font-sans max-w-sm border rounded-lg shadow-sm space-y-1">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">Ceramic Pour-Over Set</h3>
    <div class="flex items-baseline gap-2">
      <span class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900">$49</span>
      <span class="text-sm text-gray-400 line-through">$65</span>
    </div>
    <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
      <span class="text-yellow-400 text-sm">★★★★★</span>
      <span class="text-xs text-gray-400">128 reviews</span>
    </div>
    <span class="inline-block bg-green-50 text-green-700 text-xs font-medium px-2 py-0.5 rounded">In stock</span>
  </div>
</Preview>

The price is the star. The reviews are supporting detail. The stock status is confirmation.

## Don't Rely on Font Size Alone

Relying only on font size to create hierarchy is like using ketchup as your only spice.

Font size is one tool, not the only one. A tour card where the heading is bigger but everything else is regular weight still feels flat.

